aa(lp7
VAs you're all aware, we face difficult economic times.
p8
aVI come to you with a modest proposal
p9
aVfor easing the financial burden.
p10
aa(lp11
VThis idea came to me while talking to
p12
aVa physicist friend of mine at MIT.
p13
aVHe was struggling to explain something to me:
p14
aVa beautiful experiment that uses lasers to cool down matter.
p15
aVNow he confused me from the very start,
p16
aVbecause light doesn't cool things down.
p17
aVIt makes it hotter. It's happening right now.
p18
aVThe reason that you can see me standing here is because
p19
aVthis room is filled with more than 100 quintillion photons,
p20
aVand they're moving randomly through the space, near the speed of light.
p21
aVAll of them are different colors,
p22
aVthey're rippling with different frequencies,
p23
aVand they're bouncing off every surface, including me,
p24
aVand some of those are flying directly into your eyes,
p25
aVand that's why your brain is forming an image of me standing here.
p26
aa(lp27
VNow a laser is different.
p28
aVIt also uses photons, but they're all synchronized,
p29
aVand if you focus them into a beam,
p30
aVwhat you have is an incredibly useful tool.
p31
aVThe control of a laser is so precise
p32
aVthat you can perform surgery inside of an eye,
p33
aVyou can use it to store massive amounts of data,
p34
aVand you can use it for this beautiful experiment
p35
aVthat my friend was struggling to explain.
p36
aVFirst you trap atoms in a special bottle.
p37
aVIt uses electromagnetic fields to isolate the atoms
p38
aVfrom the noise of the environment.
p39
aVAnd the atoms themselves are quite violent,
p40
aVbut if you fire lasers that are precisely tuned to the right frequency,
p41
aVan atom will briefly absorb those photons
p42
aVand tend to slow down.
p43
aVLittle by little it gets colder
p44
aVuntil eventually it approaches absolute zero.
p45
aa(lp46
VNow if you use the right kind of atoms and you get them cold enough,
p47
aVsomething truly bizarre happens.
p48
aVIt's no longer a solid, a liquid or a gas.
p49
aVIt enters a new state of matter called a superfluid.
p50
aVThe atoms lose their individual identity,
p51
aVand the rules from the quantum world take over,
p52
aVand that's what gives superfluids such spooky properties.
p53
aVFor example, if you shine light through a superfluid,
p54
aVit is able to slow photons down
p55
aVto 60 kilometers per hour.
p56
aVAnother spooky property is that it flows
p57
aVwith absolutely no viscosity or friction,
p58
aVso if you were to take the lid off that bottle,
p59
aVit won't stay inside.
p60
aVA thin film will creep up the inside wall,
p61
aVflow over the top and right out the outside.
p62
aVNow of course, the moment that it does hit the outside environment,
p63
aVand its temperature rises by even a fraction of a degree,
p64
aVit immediately turns back into normal matter.
p65
aVSuperfluids are one of the most fragile things we've ever discovered.
p66
aVAnd this is the great pleasure of science:
p67
aVthe defeat of our intuition through experimentation.
