aa(lp94
VThe most surprising thing that I've learned while running this contest
p95
aVis that some scientists are now working directly with dancers on their research.
p96
aVFor example, at the University of Minnesota,
p97
aVthere's a biomedical engineer named David Odde,
p98
aVand he works with dancers to study how cells move.
p99
aVThey do it by changing their shape.
p100
aVWhen a chemical signal washes up on one side,
p101
aVit triggers the cell to expand its shape on that side,
p102
aVbecause the cell is constantly touching and tugging at the environment.
p103
aVSo that allows cells to ooze along in the right directions.
p104
aVBut what seems so slow and graceful from the outside
p105
aVis really more like chaos inside,
p106
aVbecause cells control their shape with a skeleton of rigid protein fibers,
p107
aVand those fibers are constantly falling apart.
p108
aVBut just as quickly as they explode,
p109
aVmore proteins attach to the ends and grow them longer,
p110
aVso it's constantly changing
p111
aVjust to remain exactly the same.
p112
aVNow, David builds mathematical models of this and then he tests those in the lab,
p113
aVbut before he does that, he works with dancers
p114
aVto figure out what kinds of models to build in the first place.
p115
aVIt's basically efficient brainstorming,
p116
aVand when I visited David to learn about his research,
p117
aVhe used dancers to explain it to me
p118
aVrather than the usual method: PowerPoint.
